Bitcoin's current price hovers around $19,500. While bitcoin’s correlation with stocks has fallen from its all-time high last month, its price is still largely driven by macro trigger points, like key economic data reports and central bank policy. Uncharacteristically, however, we have seen very low volatility in bitcoin's price over the last few months. Bitcoin has failed to make any significant moves since early June, with prices bouncing between an increasingly narrow range and continued high trading volumes. I do not expect that crypto's current bear market will significantly explode upwards - hence the combined probability of a combined price range of $16,000 to $24,000 is very high. I however think that the likelihood of bitcoin stagnating around the 18-19k threshold is fairly high in the remaining days until the end of the month.

The Fed's increasingly tightened monetary policy and the resulting economic downturn will exert negative pressure on Bitcoin prices. Furthermore, the growing incidence of cryptotheft from major global coin exchanges will exacerbate this situation. The market expectation of a 75 basis point increase at the next FOMC meeting in Nov will further dampen Bitcoin's price come 10/31.

Bitcoin is historically incredibly difficult to project. It is worth noting that the timeline here is short - only 21 days. Since mid-June, Bitcoin hasn't been that volatile. It strikes me that it is very unlikely that the price would be outside the $16,000-$24,000 range, which would entail a low not seen since November 2020, and a high not seen since June 2022. Where to break down within that range is more difficult, so I split largely 50-50, with a slight edge to the higher number. I think the low number goes way too low - very unlikely that Bitcoin breaks from its current price of $19,167 down into the $16,000s or $17,000s given such low volatility recently. So I'm inclined to put my highest wager on $20,000-$24,000, where the trend has been the past four months.
